Subject: [PATCH 0/3] mqueue: add capability-gated bulk peek ioctl

Linux introduced CAP_CHECKPOINT_RESTORE to represent a privileged role that
can inspect and snapshot process state for checkpoint/restore operations.
However, POSIX message queues still lack a non-destructive kernel interface
to enumerate and export queued messages. The only standard interface,
mq_receive(), is destructive, which makes it impossible to snapshot queue
contents in userspace without consuming state.

This series introduces a capability-gated ioctl, MQ_IOC_BULK_PEEK, on POSIX
mqueue files to retrieve message metadata and payload without dequeuing.
The ioctl returns a packed stream of per-message headers followed by payload
bytes, aligned to 8 bytes. Large messages can be retrieved incrementally
using start_offset and MQ_PEEK_FLAG_HAS_MORE.

Access is restricted to CAP_CHECKPOINT_RESTORE (or CAP_SYS_ADMIN) in the
queue's user namespace via ns_capable().

UAPI summary:
  - ioctl: MQ_IOC_BULK_PEEK
  - args: struct mq_bulk_peek_args
    - in:  start_idx, start_offset, max_count, buf_ptr, buf_size
    - out: out_count, next_idx, next_offset
    - reserved_in must be 0; reserved_out is set to 0
  - entry: struct mq_peek_msg_hdr (8-byte aligned)
    - total_msg_len, chunk_len, msg_prio, flags (MQ_PEEK_FLAG_HAS_MORE)
    - payload[] immediately follows

Semantics / limitations:
  POSIX mqueues are dynamic. The kernel does not maintain a stateful cursor
  across ioctl calls. If userspace performs chunked reads (start_offset > 0)
  while the queue is mutated concurrently, userspace may observe inconsistent
  results (e.g. reading the tail of a different message). Userspace is
  responsible for quiescing the queue if it requires a consistent snapshot.

Implementation notes:
  - The kernel caps the internal copy buffer at 8KB (MAX_PEEK_BUF_SIZE) to
    keep locked-time copying bounded and limit memory usage.
  - The payload copy supports msg_msg + msg_msgseg chains via a shared helper
    msg_copy_part_to_kernel().

Tests:
  A kselftest suite is included under tools/testing/selftests/mqueue/:
    - mq_chunk_tests: end-to-end payload reconstruction + boundary conditions
    - mq_edge_tests: permissions/ABI/ordering edge cases
    - mq_stress_tests: concurrent send/receive/peek workload
  Tests are capability-gated and will SKIP without sufficient privileges.

Changes since v3:
  - Added kselftests for chunk/edge/stress coverage
  - Tightened edge-case handling and validation
  - checkpatch.pl --strict (no errors)

